post_text:
MCCSD Community Update Call - Thursday 7/9 - Re-Entry Planning Status

Earlier this week, the Governor announced that on Monday the State will be releasing a reopening guidance document that all school districts need for more definitive planning for September. The Governor also stated that all school districts must submit a reopening plan to the State for approval by July 31.

While we wait for clarity from the Governor, we are continuing to plan for September. Our re-entry committees have been meeting regularly. We are developing plans based on various reopening scenarios that are educationally effective and at the same time safe for students and staff.

Parent surveys, created with our re-entry committees, will be sent out early next week, seeking your feedback and input.

Thank you in advance for your support as we work together to plan for the reopening of our schools.

To all of our students, families, and staff be well and stay safe!

Suffolk County Police Department School Bus Safety Recognition

Three MCCSD Middle School Students were selected by the Suffolk County Police Department to have their bookmark design printed to represent the Suffolk County Police Department‚Äôs initiative in School Bus Safety!

Ashleigh Raynoha from Selden Middle School and Christina Bacchi and Madeline Moceri from Dawnwood Middle School had their bookmarks selected to be displayed around Suffolk County to remind drivers - When the Red Light is Flashing, There‚Äôs No Passing! Two years ago, these students, along with 11 others won their building contest through the MCCSD Legislative Committee‚Äôs Operation School Bus Safety Bookmark Contest. Entries were then entered to the SCPD in this year‚Äôs contest. Congrats again to Ashleigh, Christina and Madeline ‚Äì leading the way for School Bus Safety in Suffolk County!
Check out their designs below!

post_text:
Summer Reading Kick Off Event at MCPL

Music of the Earth programs are unique, interactive, and really fun! We travel to five continents, exploring Australian didjeridoos, Native American drums and flutes, Indian snake charmer, crystal singing bowls, Chinese gongs, deer-hoof rattles, Aztec wind whistles, bagpipes and a lot more! Listeners learn how to make instruments, and get to sing traditional Native American chants and to make the wild animal sounds of the Australian didjeridoo.

Hey Teens! Are you interested in performing in the "Island Idol" talent/variety show at the the Middle Country Library? This year, the library has decided to make it an "Island Idol Virtual Showcase" under the pandemic circumstances. There will be an on-line informational meeting for students interested on July 6 from 3-4 PM and students can sign-up for more information here:

https://forms.gle/vRSxE5M31PFmwCDd7

This is a teen program at the library, so all Middle Country residents in Middle School and High School are eligible to participate. We've had singers, bands, dancers, solo instrumentalists, duets, quartets, even a magician! Please help get the word out!

Weekend Weather Forecast for June 19th

Hello Middle Country, my name is Lilyann Luciano and I am a Junior Meteorologist in training. I am going to share the weather forecast for this weekend.

On Saturday, June 20th, it will be a high temperature of 80 degrees and low of 65 degrees and wind 11 mph with humidity of 71%.

On Sunday, June 21st it will rain and a high temperature of 78 degrees and a low of 65 degrees wind 10 mph with humidity of 72%.

This week, I practiced my song that I will sing on the last day of school for everyone.

I would like to thank all of our teachers for working hard and teaching us each and every single day.

Time for a weather joke‚Ä¶
What did the sun want for breakfast ?

?

?

?

?

Sunny side up eggs! üòÇü§£üòÇ

post_text:
Use of Sport Fields Reminder (6/18): Fields Remain Closed

Please be advised that district fields are still not authorized for organization and group use.

We are well aware of so many of the regional, statewide and local emerging issues, intents, and motives to keep our youth athletes and teams active, fit, and competitive within hopeful future ‚Äúreturn to play‚Äù directives‚Ä¶However, those have not yet changed status that MC District fields remain closed.

Partner groups (previously permitted), or any new or ‚Äúad hoc‚Äù groups trespassing on District fields are subject (as standard) to removal by the District and/or Authorities.

In the last several weeks, unauthorized field use issues and distractions have continued to interfere with everything the District has been doing (and is trying to do) to get our District athletes back on fields as soon as allowed, and to return our community sports programs to fields as quickly and optimally as possible.

Thank you for your understanding and support on this.

Stay fit, train safe, and be well.

Hawkins Path Weekend Weather Forecast

Good Afternoon Middle Country! This is 3rd grader, Patrick Antonio Miller Ramirez. I am in training to be a Junior Meteorologist next year.

Here is the weekend weather forecast.

Saturday there will be a high of 76 degrees with a 10% chance of precipitation and a low of 59 degrees.

Sunday there will be a high of 73 degrees with a 40% chance of precipitation and a low of 60 degrees.

This week, I learned that it can take 3 days for a Monarch butterfly to make a hard case around itself, called a chrysalis.

I would like to thank Mrs. DePasquale for teaching us and for everything she has done for us.

Now for my joke:
What happens when 2 rain drops fall in love?

?

?

?

?

They become rainbows. üåàüåà

Bicycle Path Students Celebrate our 2020 Graduating Seniors

During the time we have been separated from our teachers and friends, Bicycle Path Students collaborated with the Adopt a Senior program to bring a ray of sunshine to our high school graduates. Although our year is not ending with the typical celebration they so deserve, the teachers and kindergarteners wanted them to know just how special they are while we are apart. The article was submitted and ran in NYSED for their Staying Connected Series.

Hello, this is Middle Country schools with a school budget vote and elections update, we hope this finds you and your families well.

There is still time to cast mailed votes on the school budget and elections, Governor Cuomo has just extended mail-in deadlines.

Ballots cast via mail and received by mail thru June 16th by the school district, will be eligible to be counted.

If you haven‚Äôt received your ballot, misplaced your ballot or believe you may have forgotten to sign the oath on the ballot envelope, please contact Stephanie Larkin, our district clerk, at 631-285-8011 or by email at slarkin@mccsd.net.

The counting of the ballots is now scheduled to be livestreamed on Tuesday June 16th, go to http://www.mccsd.net for more information on access to the livestreaming of the ballot count.

Hello Middle Country! This is your Chief Meteorologist, Mohsin Sheikh with your Hawkins Path Weekend Weather Forecast!

Today, I will be telling you your weekend forecast. On Saturday, it will be a high of 75 degrees and a low of 56 degrees. Well you may think it‚Äôs a perfect day to go and have a picnic but I hate to spoil your plans because it will also be a 60% chance of precipitation. On Sunday, it will be a high of 70 degrees and a low of 50 degrees. Even better there will only be a 10% chance of rain. I just want to thank Mrs. Leonard for letting us write these amazing forecasts and sharing them with the whole school and District.

Something I have learned through distance learning is how trees give out oxygen.

To wrap this Forecast up let me tell you a joke, What do you call it when it rains chickens and ducks?

?

?

?

?

?

Hello Middle Country! This is your Chief Meteorologist, Mohsin Sheikh with your Hawkins Path Weekend Weather Forecast!

Today, I will be telling you your weekend forecast. On Saturday, it will be a high of 75 degrees and a low of 56 degrees. Well you may think it‚Äôs a perfect day to go and have a picnic but I hate to spoil your plans because it will also be a 60% chance of precipitation. On Sunday, it will be a high of 70 degrees and a low of 50 degrees. Even better there will only be a 10% chance of rain. I just want to thank Mrs. Leonard for letting us write these amazing forecasts and sharing them with the whole school and District.

Something I have learned through distance learning is how trees give out oxygen.

To wrap this Forecast up let me tell you a joke, What do you call it when it rains chickens and ducks?

post_text: Congratulations Mrs. Apryle Peters, Oxhead Road 3rd grade teacher! Mrs. Peters is Brookhaven Councilman Kevin LaValle's CD3 Hero of the Day! Way to go Mrs. Peters! üéâüéâüéâ
shared_text:
Kevin J. LaValle
May 22 at 3:00 PM ¬∑

Today's CD3 Hero is Mrs. Peters.

Mrs. Peters is an Oxhead Road Elementary School teacher who has been going above and beyond, and is incredibly helpful and dedicated to supporting her students during these times of distance learning. Mrs. Peters makes learning fun and keeps her students engaged and excited to participate. Additionally, Mrs. Peters has been a tremendous help to parents through her open communication, availability, and willingness to guide both parents and students through these unique circumstances.

Thank you to not only Mrs. Peters, but to all of our Middle Country Schools and Sachem Schools teachers!

CD3 is full of everyday heroes who are providing essential services and carrying out amazing volunteer efforts during the spread of COVID-19.

We want to hear your story! Share your name, where you live, story, and picture to klavalle@brookhavenny.gov or message me here.

Hawkins Path Weekend Weather Forecast!

Hello Middle Country! It‚Äôs Hawkins Path Chief Meteorologist, Max Bowers. I am going to tell you the weather for the weekend and more.

Let‚Äôs jump right in and talk about Saturday's weather. There is a high of 64 degrees and a low of 48 degrees. There is also going to be a 90% chance of rain. Sorry, Mrs.Leonard.

Now let‚Äôs talk about Sunday‚Äôs weather. There is a high of 66 degrees and a low of 48 degrees. There is also going to be a 10% chance of rain. It is Memorial day weekend, so let‚Äôs take some time out and say thank you to all the men and women who served in the military.

One new thing I learned this week is how to skateboard.

Before I sign off I want to tell you a weather joke.
Q: What do you call winds at your birthday party?

A: Uninvited ‚Äúgusts‚Äù.

post_text: Congrats Dina Ciulla-Phillips, Brookhaven Councilman Kevin LaValle‚Äôs CD3 Hero of the Day! Dina Phillips is a proud Middle Country Parent, Resident and a Trustee on our Middle Country Board of Education. Dina, way to organize a project to recognize our Middle Country Seniors! ‚ù§Ô∏è
shared_text:
Kevin J. LaValle
May 19 at 3:00 PM ¬∑

Today's CD3 Hero Is Dina Phillips.

Dina has started two amazing programs for our Middle Country Schools class of 2020 seniors: Adopt a Cougar- Centereach High School Class of 2020, and Adopt a Wolverine- Newfield High School Class of 2020. These programs allow anyone to "adopt" a senior by sending positive messages, cards, gift baskets of support, etc. to remind them that they are not forgotten and certainly not alone. It also shows them that they are cared about not only by their families and friends, but also by their educators, peers, and this amazing community.

Thank you, Dina!

CD3 is full of everyday heroes who are providing essential services and carrying out amazing volunteer efforts during the spread of COVID-19.

We want to hear your story! Share your name, where you live, story, and picture to klavalle@brookhavenny.gov or message me here.

Congratulations Centereach HS Senior Sophia DiGiovanni!
Sophia was recognized with a $500 "Renzo & Lynette Bianchi Heckscher Centennial Scholarship Award" at the Heckscher Museum's Long Island's Best Competition for her digital photograph piece entitled "2977." Sophia explains that this is a "Drawing inspiration from Kuhn‚Äôs piece, I was intrigued by his use of contrast and lines, along with the title of the piece. Kuhn‚Äôs stylistic approach to this piece inspired me to travel to New York City and photograph the Oculus. The sun causes shadows and contrast to form on the Oculus‚Äô architecture. I chose the name 2977 because of Kuhn‚Äôs title, Memorial #22. The title 2977 represents the 2,977 people who died on September 11th, 2001."
Congrats to Sophia and her sponsor teacher Ms. Monica Holland. Pictured below is Sophia and her winning photograph!

Selden Middle School French students win big at LILT competition! üéâüéâüéâ

Congratulations to students in Mrs. Gabriela McCawley‚Äôs French classes who were big winners in the 2020 LILT (Long Island Language Teachers) Student Foreign Language Competition. The competition, which is open to all school districts in Nassau and Suffolk counties, invites students to submit entries in the categories of International Vocal Music, International Dance, Original Poetry, Poetry Recitation and Authentic Speaking Task.

The winning students include in the Poetry Recitation category: 1st place place - Addison Rothwell , 2nd place - Diya John
International Vocal Music: 1st place place- Jamey Almendarez, 2nd place- Diya John
Authentic Speaking Task : 1st place place Saitta Roy & Jasmine Recova

Congratulation to all of these students! They worked very hard and went above and beyond!

Shared by the Middle Country Public Library...

Just wanted to let you know we're hosting another Google Open Office Hours program this Thursday, May 7th at 4:00pm. It's for parents, students, and teens (K-12th grade). All are welcome to attend and there's no registration required.

Via Zoom Meeting
Zoom link: https://zoom.us/j/93113310288
Patrons are invited to enter a Google instructor‚Äôs virtual office to ask any questions they may have regarding distance learning. You are not required to attend for the entire hour, simply come in, ask your question, and choose to stay and listen to other questions or leave. Questions can be about Google Classroom, Google Drive, Docs, Slides, Sheets, Accessibility, staying organized, staying motivated, and more!

Also, the recordings of the Google Classroom programs we just hosted in April are all available on the library's YouTube channel at: https://www.youtube.com/MiddleCountryPublicLibrary

~MCPL Teen Services

post_text:
MCCSD Community Update Call Friday 4/17

As you may have heard, Governor Cuomo has extended school closures until May 15. School right now is so different from what our children ‚Äì and adults ‚Äì are used to, but learning has to continue. This makes it even more important that your children are signing in everyday to Google Classroom or viewing eBoards and participating in instruction. Beginning on Monday, we will be following up on any student who hasn‚Äôt connected with her or his teacher to find out why ‚Äì and how we might further assist. Our children need to be prepared, as best they can be, for a return to school.

Our Grab and Go Breakfast and Lunch Program is running strong. Please make sure to check http://www.mccsd.net of information on the program ‚Äì remember, it is available for every student, pre-k through grade 12, in our community.

Please stay safe, practice social distancing and stay connected. We miss our students!
